      "content": "December 5th, 1887. One cannot ignore the innate qualities that distinguish peoples; the temperament forged by centuries of rigorous Western discipline proves markedly different from the prevailing native disposition. Their natural inclination often seems swayed by ephemeral passions rather than the steady logic that guides my own people. This fundamental difference in constitution dictates that guidance, not mere tolerance, is required for their betterment. The British spirit, inherently more suited to governance, must therefore assume the mantle of necessary tutelage over these more volatile subjects.",
      "source": "target",
